[6] South America (Brazil)
Date: Wed 9 Jan 2019
Source: Eurosurveillance [abridged, edited]
http://dx.doi.org/10.2807/1560-7917.ES.2019.24.2.1800663


Citation: Elidio GA, de Franca GVA, Caselli PF, et al. Measles outbreak: preliminary report on a case series of the first 8070 suspected cases, Manaus, Amazonas state, Brazil, February to November 2018. Euro Surveill 2019;24(2):pii=1800663.

[See source URL for references, table, figures and full report of the measles outbreak in Brazil. - Mod.LK]

In February 2018, a measles outbreak was reported in the state of Roraima, Brazil and was found to be associated with the ongoing measles outbreak in Venezuela [1]. As of 10 Dec 2018, 349 cases have been confirmed [2]. Between 2001 and 2017, the Amazonas state did not report any confirmed measles cases [3]. Here, we report the ongoing measles outbreak in Manaus capital of the Amazonas state in Brazil. The north of Amazonas state borders Venezuela. Manaus has 2 145 444 inhabitants.

In 1969, the Ministry of Health (MoH) in Brazil established that all suspected measles cases seeking health services must be reported to the local authorities; cases must also be registered in the National System of Notifiable Diseases (Sinan) [4].

The 1st laboratory-confirmed case of the ongoing outbreak was a woman in her early 20s living in the northern district of Manaus. She had rash onset on 21 Feb 2018 and presented with fever, cough, coryza and conjunctivitis. She was identified during the investigation of her one-year-old child's case, who had rash onset on 1 Mar 2018 and presented the same symptoms as the mother. Laboratory confirmation of measles was obtained on 23 Mar 2018.

The D8 genotype measles virus was identified in a urine sample from the infant, which was identical to the one that is circulating in Venezuela; genotyping also showed that it was a wild-type measles virus. The mother reported having had contact with 3 Venezuelan migrants in January 2018.

Although the current available information suggests a link between the outbreaks in Venezuela and Manaus, further molecular epidemiological studies are needed to help understand the reintroduction of measles in the municipality.

From 6 Feb to 3 Nov 2018, 8070 suspected measles cases were reported; the median interval between the date of notification and the date of the final classification of the case was 37 days (range, 0-140 days). All the confirmed cases were Brazilians. The incidence of measles among confirmed cases was 75.3 per 100 000 inhabitants; the incidence was higher among infants (1003.9 per 100 000 inhabitants) and children 1 to 4 years of age (175.3 per 100 000 inhabitants). Up to 3 Nov 2018, the northern district accounted for the largest number of cases (2753 cases) (Table 1).

