[7] Philippines
Date: Thu 10 Jan 2019
Source: DavaoToday [edited]
http://davaotoday.com/main/economy/health/city-health-office-intensifies-public-info-campaign-on-measles-immunization/


The Davao City Health Office is now intensifying its efforts to explain the need for measles vaccination, as many are still reluctant to avail of immunization because of the Dengvaxia issue. Curtis C. Lazarraga of the City Health Office (CHO) said, in a press conference on Thu [10 Jan 2019], the agency "is having a hard time" in reaching out to communities because many are still doubtful of the safety of undergoing vaccination.

"It is still very hard to convince the public that vaccination is needed especially for children because they are still afraid that it may cause them harm," said Lazarraga. Lazarraga added that of the 90% total target population, only 30% to 40% were vaccinated in 2018. He said this is still a conservative estimate.

It was in February 2016 when Health Secretary Janette Garin hosted the nationwide launch of Dengvaxia, and in April of the same year the government started the school-based dengue immunization program that gave 3 doses of vaccines to 830 000 students every 6 months after the Philippines approved the sale of Sanofi Pasteur's Dengvaxia vaccine. Dengvaxia is the world's 1st dengue vaccine.

In November 2017, the manufacturer, Sanofi Pasteur, announced that Dengvaxia posed a risk to people who had not previously been exposed to dengue. This followed the withdrawal of approval of the Food and Drug Administration after citing safety concerns. This set off a panic among parents of vaccinated children that resulted in public outrage.

Lazarraga said the CHO has been intensifying its campaign to the public, going house to house in the community to further explain the need to let their children be immunized. The World Health Organization reported that cases of measles in the Philippines have increased up to 367% in 2018, reaching up to 17 298 cases, compared with 2017 when there were only 3706 cases.

In October last year [2018] around 300 cases were reported in Bicol region, resulting in the death of 6 individuals.

"It is a challenge how the CHO will reach out to the remaining percentage of the public that needs vaccination. But we will do all efforts," said Lazarraga. No less than Mayor Sara Duterte is leading the campaign and asking the public to let their children avail of the free vaccination from the CHO, but Lazarraga said there is a lot to do this year to gain public trust.

[Byline: Kath M. Cortez]

--
